br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Inshore 28 miles</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 13] Bristol Big Green Week&nbsp;</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">14th to 20th June 2015</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">In harbour</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 14] Bristol to Milford Haven</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">21st to 27th June 2015</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Coastal 107 miles</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 15] Milford Haven to Dublin</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">28th June to 4th July 2015</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Offshore 120 miles</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">IRELAND &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 16] Dublin to Belfast</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">5th to 11th July 2015</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Coastal 110 miles</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">NORTHERN IRELAND</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 17] Belfast to Barrow in Furness</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">12th to 18th July 2015</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Coastal / Offshore 110 miles</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">UK</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 18] Barrow in Furness to St Katherine Dock, London</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">2nd to 16th August</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Offshore 650 miles</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Special Project with Estuary Group </span></em></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 19] St Katherine&rsquo;s Dock to St Katherines&rsquo;s Dock</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">17th to 21st August</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">[Leg 20] St Katherine&rsquo;s Dock to St Katherines&rsquo;s Dock</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">24th to 28st August</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Coastal</span></p>\r\n',2,1,'2015-03-05 20:36:50',NULL,'2015-03-05 09:07:30','2015-03-31 08:04:00','joining-floodtide-navigate'),(11,'Jacomina','<div style=\"page-break-after: always\"><span style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"page-break-after: always\"><span style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"page-break-after: always\"><span style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"page-break-after: always\"><span style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/24/content_P7260220.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jacomina is a Swan 46 Mk1 sloop designed by German Frers and built by Nautor in Finland in 1984.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like all Swan yachts she is comfortable, fast and very seaworthy. Jacomina herself is well travelled and has made several Atlantic crossings as well as plenty of cruising and racing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The yacht has 7 berths arranged across three cabins; fo&#39;csle, saloon and aft cabin. There are two heads (loos) with sink and shower with hot and cold running water. The galley has a three burner cooker with grill and oven, a double sink, refridgerator and freezer. There is heating and even air conditioning!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/25/content_4137602_2_20121112032137_11_0.jpg\" style=\"height:217px; width:606px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main saloon has a large drop leaf table that is good for working and eating together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/27/content_P1380684.jpg\" style=\"height:300px; width:400px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jacomina is fully equipped for offshore sailing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',2,0,NULL,NULL,'2015-03-05 11:28:47','2015-03-05 20:31:33','jacomina'),(12,'...on the subject of boats ','<h3 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"color:#aaa; font-style:italic\"><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/123535256\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/31/content_Screen_Shot_jpeg.jpg\" style=\"height:500px; width:800px\" /></a></h3>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">FLOODTIDE NAVIGATE CALAIS - BOULOGNE 27 MARCH 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">L.A: &quot;How do you feel about the Floodtide Navigate project from a sailing perspective?&quot;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">J.E: &quot;Well... (thinks) It is lovely to have Jacomina which is a Swan 46. It&rsquo;s quite a subtle difference in the sailing experience and hard to describe. I trust it to look after everyone on board and that is a really important thing. I&rsquo;ve been scared on sailing boats enough times to know that I don&rsquo;t want to be in a position where I feel that the boat is not going to look after me. So&hellip; &nbsp;it&rsquo;s so exciting to have an opportunity to sail a good sailing boat; that is good for the Floodtide project but also other further possible projects. And also if Floodtide phase two could possibly happen, then a boat that has excellent sailing capability would be good.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">Floodtide is an usual project from a sailing point of view. The idea that we will decide to go places that we think we can do an interesting Floodtide performance; it might have good performers, a good place to perform and those things put a demand on the navigation. It&rsquo;s different to going on a sailing holiday where you choose to hop one nice marina or anchorage to another. In this case, you might have to go somewhere like, for example, Barrow in Furness. That&rsquo;s perfectly fine place to navigate to, but it&rsquo;s not a common place, as far I know, for holiday makers to sail to. There is nothing particularly difficult about it but it illustrates that we have to sail places that are slightly challenging from a navigation point of view. And again having a rugged boat might mean we have to anchor or be on a mooring in an uncomfortable place for a while and need to be resourceful and self sufficient, those kind of things; not be too dependant on stepping ashore to a cosy marina all the time. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s nice to have a decent dinghy that we can explore creeks and be able to row </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:15px\">ashore to a venue and that kind of thing if we can&rsquo;t step ashore. So it&rsquo;s all to do with ruggedness in a way...and resources.&quot;</span></p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-03-29 00:00:00',NULL,'2015-03-06 14:29:54','2015-03-29 17:38:25','on-the-subject-of-boats'),(14,'Floodtide notation version 2.0','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><a href=\"http://www.floodtide.eu/play\">http://www.floodtide.eu/play</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve finally posted the new Floodtide notation version 2.0. It has proper note durations (rather than just quavers) and handles sharps and flats (fairly) sensibly. It might not look so different but is the result of about 5 months of re-writing. Am hoping it opens up lots of new opportunities for Floodtide and leads to even nicer performances!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are a jazz musician you might want to try the Harmony &gt; Jazz Chord Scales option which can be a little scary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Needles to say I am still working at finding better ways of turning tide into music.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please have a play and let me know how it goes for you.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"mailto:john@informal.org?subject=Floodtide%20notation\">John</a>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',2,1,'2015-03-07 11:54:00',NULL,'2015-03-07 11:53:07','2015-03-07 11:55:49','floodtide-notation-version-2-0'),(15,'Floodtide Navigate - Leg one : Gill Scheuer and AndrÃ© Schmidt, Antwerp to Boulogne ','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/124021831\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/32/content_Andre_cropped_for_twitter.png\" style=\"height:681px; width:624px\" /></a></p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-04-03 12:46:46',NULL,'2015-04-03 10:32:16','2015-04-03 12:46:46','floodtide-navigate-leg-one-gill-scheuer-and-andre-schmidt-antwerp-to-boulogne'),(16,'Floodtide Navigate : excerpt from performance Saturday 11 April 15.00 in Brest, Brittany ','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/124744753\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/34/content_Screen_Shot_2015-04-13_at_13.27.50.png\" style=\"height:392px; width:800px\" /></a>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Excerpt from live streamed solo performance by John Eacott using Floodtide jazz notation, Saturday 11 April 2015 at 15.00 in Brest Brittany</p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-04-13 11:21:27',NULL,'2015-04-13 11:17:45','2015-04-13 11:30:44','floodtide-navigate-excerpt-from-performance-saturday-11-april-15-00-in-brest-brittany'),(17,'17 April St Nazaire | Short Floodtide fanfare to celebrate the arrival (finally) of the banner!','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/125390218\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/36/content_banner.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></a></p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-04-19 18:04:37',NULL,'2015-04-19 10:20:57','2015-04-19 18:04:37','17-april-st-nazaire-short-floodtide-fanfare-to-celebrate-the-arrival-finally-of-the-banner'),(19,'Floodtide Navigate : excerpt from performance Saturday 18 April 15.00 in St Nazaire, Brittany ','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/125468442\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/37/content_Screen_Shot_2015-04-20_at_16.54.39.png\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many thanks to the performers:&nbsp; Ana&iuml;s Marchand, Antoine B&egrave;gu&egrave;re,&nbsp; Arnoud Marchand, Benjamin Vincelot, Christopher Havard, Corentin Marchand, Clara Bodet, Claude Bulourde, Meas Yunsan and Yann Bouvais.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And a very special thank you to&nbsp; <span style=\"font-family:pt sans\">J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Joy</span> and R&eacute;gine Fertillet for their invaluable help, support and enthusiasm.</p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-04-20 15:07:52',NULL,'2015-04-20 15:07:21','2015-04-20 15:07:52','floodtide-navigate-excerpt-from-performance-saturday-18-april-15-00-in-st-nazaire-brittany'),(21,'Floodtide navigate : the journey between Brest and Saint Nazaire 15-16 April','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/126030397\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/39/content_DSCN0106.JPG\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" />https://vimeo.com/126030397</a></p>\r\n',2,1,'2015-04-26 07:50:36',NULL,'2015-04-26 07:50:36','2015-04-26 07:53:47','floodtide-navigate-the-journey-between-brest-and-saint-nazaire-15-16-april'),(23,' Floodtide Navigate Haikus : Friday 3 April - Thursday 9 April 2015, Boulogne - Brest, France','<p>FLOODTIDE NAVIGATE | THIRD LEG | HAIKUS BY LENA AUGUSTINSIN</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Friday 3 April Boulogne France</em><br />\r\nPreparing to cross<br />\r\nand a long voyage ahead<br />\r\nFixing and doing</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Saturday 4 April&nbsp; Boulogne - Fecamp France</em><br />\r\nUp to a seven<br />\r\nFull sails on Jacomina<br />\r\nWe are very tired</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Sunday 5 April Fecamp - Cherbourg , France</em><br />\r\nA warm friendly sail<br />\r\nmake a bright and happy trip<br />\r\nto umbrella town</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Monday 6 April Cherbourg - L&rsquo;Aber Wrac&rsquo;h France</em><br />\r\nTwenty-four hours<br />\r\nFollowed by the sun and moon<br />\r\nBlessed by a porpoise</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Tuesday 7 April Cherbourg -L&rsquo;aber Wrac&rsquo;h France</em><br />\r\nNo spa treatment in<br />\r\nthe world can beat the hot shower<br />\r\nat L&rsquo;Aber Wrac&rsquo;h in France</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Wednesday 8 April L&rsquo;Aber Wrac&rsquo;h - Brest France</em><br />\r\nWe are getting good<br />\r\nand getting it good as well<br />\r\non the big blue swell</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Thursday 9 April Brest France</em><br />\r\nThe heating is on<br />\r\nand the sun is so welcomed<br />\r\nWhat else do you need?</p>\r\n',2,1,'2015-05-02 10:25:17',NULL,'2015-04-28 11:13:28','2015-05-02 10:25:17','floodtide-navigate-haikus-friday-3-april-thursday-9-april-2015-boulogne-brest-france'),(25,'Leeward, bow, windward, stern | the sound of water and wind on the bay of Biscay ','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/126667350\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/41/content_leeward__bow__windward__stern.001.jpg\" style=\"height:483px; width:787px\" />https://vimeo.com/126667350</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This audio is about the sound of the sea when sailing on Jacomina, the Floodtide sailing yacht, between Saint Nazaire, France and Bilbao, Spain. Recordings of the sea and wind; leeward, on the bow, windward and from the stern</p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-05-02 10:23:26',NULL,'2015-05-02 10:23:26','2015-05-02 10:24:10','leeward-bow-windward-stern-the-sound-of-water-and-wind-on-the-bay-of-biscay'),(26,'Floodtide Navigate : Gbop plays live tidal flow 2 May 2015, Copenhagen Denmark','<p><a href=\"https://vimeo.com/126680816\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/42/content_517207675_295x166.jpg\" style=\"height:166px; width:295px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>https://vimeo.com/126680816</p>\r\n',2,1,'2015-05-03 00:00:00',NULL,'2015-05-02 16:40:19','2015-05-02 16:41:23','floodtide-navigate-gbop-plays-live-tidal-flow-2-may-2015-copenhagen-denmark'),(27,'Captain\'s log - getting Jacomina','<p><strong>Monday 9th March 2015</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>After a tough negotiation I arrived in Willemstad by hired a car.&nbsp; Jacomina was equipped with a large sail inventory of which many would be taken home to London. At the small marina the Swan 46 stood alongside a pontoon and it felt big. Since we had sold our much loved Contessa 26 &lsquo;Graying&rsquo; in 1999 an unthinkable amount of time browsing magazines and online had been spent working out the boat that would follow her. While on holiday in Sweden I had seen an advert for a Swan and the thought occurred that it would be possible to own one which had previously been unimaginable. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/43/content_20150309_114723.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>A new owner of Jacomina on hand-over day</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Swan yachts have been made at the Nautor boatyard in Finland since the late 1960s. The company set out to make the finest fibreglass production yachts money could buy and quickly make a spectacular impact. In the first Whitbread Round the World Race in 1973 - an unthinkably difficult race at the time - Swan&rsquo;s finished 1st, 3rd and 4th as well as winning competitions at all other levels. The yachts are also wonderful cruising boats with well thought out and beautifully made interiors. But the greatest luxury for Lena and I in choosing one is their robust construction and great sailing ability.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Launched in 1984 for UK owners under a different name, Jacomina had been raced and cruised on both sides of the Atlantic as well as the Mediterranean. Former Dutch champion dinghy sailors Willem and Els had owned her since 2001 and cruised her in Europe, the UK and Scandinavia. Willem, a ship builder now in his late 60s had maintained Jacomina with endless care.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I stepped up onto the large teak deck with mixed feelings of excitement and responsibility that owning such a yacht would bring. While collecting my thoughts Willem appeared and we greeted politely. I tried to apologise for the protracted negotiation. Willem simply said &lsquo;I have nothing good to say about that.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A broker arrived to act as witness for the sale. There was some discussion about aspects of maintenance and the broker asked that we do the formal business first and leave discussion until afterwards. The three of us sat down on the U shaped sofa in the saloon (where I am sitting writing this) and Willem produced a folder of registration and other documents. On agreeing that they were in order the&nbsp; handover contract was signed by Willem and I. The broker turned to me offering congratulations. I shook hands with Willem who with a tear in his tough shipbuilder&rsquo;s eye said &lsquo;look after her.&rsquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/44/content_20150309_153219.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>A cockpit full of sails</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the broker departed Willem spent time with me explaining detail about systems and maintenance followed by a couple of journeys to his home collecting sails and other equipment before filling the car with the rest which I drove to London.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lena and I arrived at Jacomina on Thursday 12th March with our dog Dizzy. Lena had not seen the yacht although she had come to view others. I was pleased that she liked the look and feel straight away and the well maintained interior would made a great impression. We spent the day getting to know our new surroundings, buying some bits and pieces and I made a celibratory dinner of roast pork.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/45/content_20150312_190822.jpg\" style=\"height:480px; width:640px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Selfie: Our first evening aboard Jacomina</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following day we were keen to get underway to get the feel of her. Although not particularly superstitious however we felt that it may not bode well to make our first step of our epic voyage on Friday 13th. So after taking care to check engine and lines we left the berth to practise docking finally parking in the opposite direction so that the water hose would reach and we could begin to flush and fill the tanks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Saturday 14th March 2015</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>At 1032 we slipped the berth at Willemstad on a chilly overcast day as new owners. Our first destination for the Floodtide Navigate project was Antwerp 60 miles away along inland waterways. But our first stop was 200 metres later at the fuel pontoon. Despite being an RYA Yachtmaster Instructor given the tense dealings with Willem who is well known in Willemstad I felt relief that we parked without incident. it would have been embarrassing to have made a pigs ear as he would hear about it. Jacomina felt like a big step up in terms of complexity. We only had to fill the starboard tank which was convenient because at that stage I hadn&rsquo;t worked out how to get fuel into the port one. At last we left Willemstad towards Volkerak Sluis half a mile away and tied up on a large pier waiting for the lock to open. &nbsp;On exiting the lock we cut the engine and unfurled the impressive genoa allowing us to sail at 7 knots in a 12 knot breeze. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/46/content_20150314_121615.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Our first journey on Jacomina in chilly conditions.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Half an hour later we pulled into Dintelsas, a functional medium sized harbour where a local boaty and member of the yacht club collected our mooring fee. As the weather was cold and rainy we stayed the next day but enjoyed a walk into the local town for a beer and a singalong of football songs with some Feyenoord fans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Monday March 16th 2015</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Slipped berth with icy decks at 1025 and arrived&nbsp; six hours and one lock later in Wemeldinge. During the trip I had a look at the radar which worked nicely. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/47/content_20150316_113205.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>The vintage but beautifully working Furuno radar</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following day after negotiating the busy Schelte river and officious port control we arrived in Willemdock marina Antwerp ready to begin Floodtide Navigate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/48/content_20150320_091731.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Jacomina in Antwerp</em></p>\r\n',2,0,'2015-05-10 16:11:45',NULL,'2015-05-10 16:05:47','2015-05-10 16:28:55','captain-s-log-getting-jacomina'),(28,'Anna- Karin Andersson interviews John Eacott about Floodtide in Pasajes, Basque country, Northern Spain, 8 May 2015','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/lena-augustinson/sets/john-eacott-interview-by-anna\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/43/content_20150309_114723.jpg\" style=\"height:300px; width:400px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>https://soundcloud.com/lena-augustinson/sets/john-eacott-interview-by-anna</p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-06-09 10:24:20',NULL,'2015-06-09 10:23:21','2015-06-09 10:24:20','anna-karin-andersson-interviews-john-eacott-about-floodtide-in-pasajes-basque-country-northern-spain-8-may-2015'),(29,'In conversation: Jerome Joy and John Eacott, Saint Nazaire, April 2015','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/lena-augustinson/jerome-joy-john-eacott-in-conversation-april-2015\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/36/content_banner.jpg\" style=\"height:600px; width:800px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This informal conversation between the musicians and composers Jerome Joy and John Eacott took place in Jerome Joy&#39;s garden in Saint Nazaire, France in April 2015.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Information about Jerome Joy http://joy.nujus.net</p>\r\n\r\n<p>https://soundcloud.com/lena-augustinson/jerome-joy-john-eacott-in-conversation-april-2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',1,1,'2015-06-09 10:41:25',NULL,'2015-06-09 10:35:04','2015-06-09 10:41:25','in-conversation-jerome-joy-and-john-eacott-saint-nazaire-april-2015'),(30